   Attorneys for Leona Helmsley said the hotel queen should
have been acquitted of tax-evasion charges last year because
she actually overpaid her taxes.
   In December, Mrs. Helmsley was sentenced to four years in
prison and fined $7.2 million after being convicted of
evading $1.2 million in taxes in 1983-85. Currently free on
bail pending her appeal, Mrs. Helmsley also is on trial in
New York state court for alleged state tax violations.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The appellate brief maintains that before Mrs. Helmsley
could be convicted of evading taxes, prosecutors had to prove
that she actually owed taxes for those three years. The brief
was filed with a federal appeals court in New York by a team
of defense attorneys led by Harvard Law School Professor Alan
Dershowitz.
   "The defense introduced unrebutted testimony clearly
establishing that the Helmsleys' joint federal income tax
returns for each of those years overstated their joint
taxable income and tax," the brief said. Mrs. Helmsley's
husband, real-estate magnate Harry Helmsley, was initially
charged in the case but later was dropped as a defendant
after the trial judge found him mentally unfit to stand
trial.
   The brief accuses the government of being overzealous in
its pursuit of the case. "The government should not have been
`surprised' by the fact that a re-examination and
recalculation resulted in the Helmsleys having actually
overpaid their taxes during these years," the brief said.
   The attorneys said Mrs. Helmsley was charged with evading
only 3% of the total taxes that the U.S. said she owed for
those three years. Prosecutors should have expected that a
review of the tax returns could have turned up enough new
information to offset the relatively small amount that
allegedly was evaded, the brief said.
   The recalculation involves mistakes that Mrs. Helmsley's
attorneys say were made regarding the depreciation of certain
property.
   Mrs. Helmsley's attorneys claim she overpaid taxes by
$21,000 to $477,000 annually during the three years. Similar
claims were made during the trial but were rejected by Judge
John Walker.
