   FALSE-AD CLAIMS about home ice-cream maker melt in court.
   A federal judge in Manhattan dismissed a false-advertising
lawsuit brought by home ice-cream maker giant Nikkal
Industries Inc. against Salton Inc., one of its newer
competitors. The judge said that even though some of Salton's
marketing could be potentially misleading, the company didn't
use deceptive advertising to promote its product.
   A main issue in the case was the ice cream's
"scoopability," referring to whether dessert made in the
non-electric ice-cream makers is firm enough to be scooped
onto a cone. But after hearing from two professors who served
as expert witnesses -- including one who had developed a
"scoopability" standard -- Judge Charles Tenney said the
disputed characteristic is too subjective to measure.
   Judge Tenney also said it is unlikely customers were
misled by pictures of sculptured mashed potatoes made to look
like scoops of ice cream in Salton's advertisements. The ads
-- which were directed at buyers for retail stores, rather
the general public -- used mashed potatoes in the pictures
because ice cream would melt under the lights.
   Judge Tenney rejected Nikkal's claims that the Salton ads
caused the company to lose millions of dollars in sales.
Instead, Nikkal itself was partly to blame, the judge said.
   "Nikkal's own marketing strategy played the predominant
role in the decline of sales. . . . Despite the increased
competition from companies such as Salton, Nikkal pursued a
strategy that didn't adequately meet the challenge of the
increasingly crowded market," Judge Tenney said in his
opinion. For instance, the judge said, Nikkal ignored its
sales staff's recommendations that it lower prices.
   Officials of Nikkal, based in Virginia Beach, Va., and
company attorneys couldn't be reached for comment.
   Until 1986, when Salton introduced its Big Chill line,
Nikkal was virtually the only distributor of this type of
compact ice-cream maker. The judge said the main purpose of
Nikkal's lawsuit was to prevent Salton from being able to
compete.
   Salton's ice-cream-maker business is now owned by closely
held Sevco Inc. of Deerfield, Ill.
