   EX-XEROX COUNSEL leaves post at Latham &amp; Watkins.
   After just 14 months, Robert S. Banks has left his job as
counsel at the New York office of Latham &amp; Watkins, a Los
Angeles law firm with more than 500 lawyers. He has agreed to
serve as outside general counsel of Keystone Holdings Inc., a
company controlled by Texas financier Robert M. Bass.
Keystone's principal asset is American Savings Bank of
Stockton, Calif., a Latham client.
   Mr. Banks, long regarded in legal circles as the chief
architect of the modern corporate law department, surprised
many when he left his post as general counsel of Xerox Corp.
to join Latham. There, he worked primarily as a consultant
for in-house general counsel seeking ways to cut costs and
deal more effectively with outside law firms.
   The unusual arrangement resulted in some
conflict-of-interest problems with other clients at the firm
and difficulties in promoting the new service, said Clinton
R. Stevenson, the former managing partner of Latham who
worked with Mr. Banks on the project.
   "If we had been separate from the law firm it would not
have been as difficult to solve the problems. But I had no
desire to be separate from the law firm," said Mr. Stevenson.
   Mr. Banks said there was also some tension about his
message that companies can sharply cut their outside legal
bills. "It's very difficult to provide the kinds of services
that I want to provide within the framework of a law firm.
I'm still not looked on warmly by partners at law firms," Mr.
Banks said.
   Mr. Banks said he will divide his time between California
and New Canaan, Conn., where he has set up an office. He said
he hopes to help cut American Savings's litigation and
outside legal costs.
